I've been meaning to try this place out for a while now and finally got the opportunity to. I wish it was under better circumstances with a full offering of their menu, but I'll take what I can get. First and foremost, love that they have an open kitchen, best thing in the world a restaurant could have. If anyone tells you otherwise, they're a liar and have no idea of what is aesthetically pleasing to the human eye. Secondly, I loved the patio area, it had a really rustic feel to it. The choice in music was a bit of a roller coaster for me. It had to be a playlist from someone's iPod back from the 90s or something, I swear; however, I digress. The food was absolutely amazing though. I give a 4 out of 5 for a good reason and I'll explain later on. For appetizers, ordered some fries, empanadas and elote. Reason number one: elote was whole instead of cut. Given, it was absolutely delicious, but it was a complete mess to have to cut it up to eat. Had I not been sharing, I would've just eaten it whole from the cob itself, but I'm sure it's a shareable dish, which is why a knife was provided with the dish. The fries are addictive and I couldn't stop munching on them. They were perfectly fried to a nice crisp and went well with the ketchup and aioli. Switching between the two definitely helped and assisted in the moreish-ness to it. Nothing bad to say about the empanadas except I wish there was more than just three to a serving. Moving onto the entrees now which were spectacular, but still had a bit of faults in each individual one. Starting with the Lobster BLT, it's a monster of a sandwich. I don't think the choice of bread was the best to sandwich everything in between, but I understand why the choice of brioche was used instead of normal toasted bread. I think sourdough would've been a good substitute, to cut the richness of the lobster and the fattiness of the bacon. The chicken and waffles was absolutely amazing. It was perfect from start to finish except the portion size was a bit off. I ended up with more waffle than chicken in the end, but that's a personal opinion and up for debate. The chicken was perfectly cooked: crispy, juicy, moist, tender, everything was just amazing about this dish. The sunny side egg on top made it all the better. The final entree was Ahi Tuna. I'm not a huge fan of tuna but it was an entree someone in my group ordered. The tuna cannot be had on its own here, it needs everything that is served with it. From the rice to the salad, to the sauce/dressing. Losing any of those items would just make the dish very bland and boring. I would've preferred the tuna to be either fully cooked and shredded perhaps, or possibly just raw and cubed into bite sized pieces. Again, this is a matter of personal opinion and preference, but this is my overall review of the place. I definitely recommend and will definitely be visiting once again, in the very near future.

Shakshuka  A fancy-licious meal at a fancy-licious restaurant. Shakshuka might be the newest kid on the block when it comes to brunch - ever heard of it? Sounds like a dance-form, or a magic spell, doesn’t it?  Well, the dish traces its roots back to North Africa and is very popular in the Middle East. Poached eggs in a tomato and red pepper-based curry spiced with cumin, paprika and cayenne served with bread or pita, meat is optional. Nothing less than heavenly for all savory brunch loyalists (including us). It’s pretty light and healthy, too.  A good mix of antioxidants from the peppers; protein from the eggs and the meat; fat from the eggs; and carbs from the bread. The one we had was super spicy, too. – Bonus for spice lovers.  𝐓𝐡𝐞 𝐑𝐞𝐬𝐭𝐚𝐮𝐫𝐚𝐧𝐭 A fantastic place to dine at. The interiors draw inspiration from the neighborhoods history and the industrial innovation of that era. With an amazing patio, it's a perfect spot to hang-out during spring and summertime.

Lovely venue with pretty good service. There is a free coat check, so take advantage of that in the winter. I ordered the salmon at dinner, which came with a cream sauce on the side and took up half the plate. I am very lactose intolerant, so I tried my best to avoid it, but inevitably I could not easy part of my meal. To be fair, I did forget to ask our server if there was dairy in the dish & he later confirmed, but did not ask why I asked in the first place (you'd think it'd be a hint), but I don't hold it against him. So, I simply ate around it.  I'd gotten married the day before my group dined here, so I was offered free dessert, but I had to ask for the dessert menu (they forgot to bring them initially), then once the bill came, the dessert was listed on it, so I had to awkwardly ask if I was still going to get the free dessert I was told I'd receive. Our server did apologize for the mistake and removed it from our receipt, but I still wish I didn't have to ask. As an fyi, only one dessert is dairy free - the sorbet.  All in all, I enjoyed the experience, but one last thing to note: the music was pretty loud  inside, so it was difficult to hold a conversation with anyone other than the person seated next to you. Just something to keep in mind when picking a place with good food AND conversation potential.

The Dawson is very mediocre in some areas &  excels in others. I've had strange experiences here with that! I'll just detail my last visit though. We went for brunch during restaurant week. The menu looked incredible & I was very excited about it. Right up my alley. The first dish was an avocado toast. The description was fabulous; soft scrambled eggs, burrata cheese, roasted tomatoes, pesto.. I couldn't wait. But it was terrible. Flavorless with all those toppings! No salt at all. A pile of salad on top, literally one tomato, (which carried all the flavor) a tiny dollop of pesto & the strangest texas style white bread for an avocado toast. Super disappointing. Second course was the brussel sprout hash which was great. The potatoes & egg were quite overdone but the flavors were all there & it had salt! Completely opposite from the first dish. Third was a horchata tres leches cake & a chocolate mousse. Both were outstanding. Especially the tres leches cake. One of the best desserts I've ever had. Obviously the meal was all over the place. We weren't greeted by our server for the first 10 minutes of being seated. Service was lackluster after they finally arrived. Scarce even. I was also given a dirty cup & after pointing it out I was told it was a stain which I then proceeded to scrape off easily with my fingernail. All in all I wouldn't really recommend this place. Not sure the high rating. Location? Large space? Chicken fried lobster? I'd go back for dessert & a drink but I'd eat a meal elsewhere. The Dawson needs a lot of refining.

Overall: The ambiance and drinks shine brightly at The Dawson.  The good: The drinks are spot on, no matter what you're in the mood for. Our larger table got a healthy mixture of wine, beer, cocktails, and everyone seemed happy with their decisions. My personal choice, The Buddy System, was unique and robust in flavor. The patio was a highlight as well, with a varied mixture of greenery to go along with the "suburban deck" vibe. The elotes were incredible and the tuna ceviche was also a standout food-wise.  The not-so-good: Some of the food was great but others were misses. The famous chicken fried lobster was disappointing due to being surprisingly too fried and chicken-y, with not enough emphasis on the lobster side of it. Plus it was far too small, with each person only get a bite or two if you split with 4 people. Also, the meatballs were bland and the broth they were served in wasn't very flavorful or spicy.  Atmosphere: 9/10 Service: 8/10 Food: 7.5/10

Quick to clear drinks, not so quick to ask if you'd like another - or to take your order at all. If you aren't that hungry and don't mind waiting what seems like forever, this is your place.
